Abstract

Students were shown messages that emphasize the benefit of math to the community. We hoped this would increase the rate students master new math skills. Across the whole population there was a small, negative effect. However, the messages affected different groups of users in different ways. There was a small, negative effect on supervised (coached) students. In contrast, there was a substantial, positive effect for experienced, uncoached users. This group accounts for approximately 5% of users and 16% of correctly answered problems. Members of this group attained 13% more level 3 masteries in the treatment condition than control. This effect did not appear to dissipate over the 30 days over which data were examined. We hope to revise this intervention to target the users who are most likely to benefit from it.

About this Document

This is a working draft. Its intended audience includes staff at PERTS and Khan Academy. Please address comments and questions to Dave Paunesku,

Study Summary

Background

This is one of two social psychology experiments run at Khan Academy as part of the Mindset Challenge. The intervention materials were designed by Belanger, Steinberg, and Diekman at the invitation of PERTS and Khan Academy. The project was funded by the Raikes Foundation. Experiments were implemented by Ben Haley and Daniel Greene.

Hypothesis

Students who see messages emphasizing the benefit of math to the community will be more engaged and outperform those who see no messages.

Treatments

Students are shown messages above exercises that emphasize the benefit of math to people and communities (as opposed to scientists isolated on secret island fortresses).

Whole Sample Results

Across the whole population of Khan Academy users, the results started promising and became bad. Concretely, promotion to mastery level 3 was up about +2% for the first few months, but dropped to about -2% with time.

Similar results were seen for problem correct and return visits. See the mad scientist dashboard for more details.

Subgroup Results

The intervention had different effects on different groups of users. It appeared to have a small (~2%), negative effect on coached users (those whose progress is supervised by a teacher, parent, etc.). here is tentative evidence that this effect dissipated over time, as users were exposed to the intervention for a longer period of time.

There was also a larger, positive effect among experienced, uncoached users those who had at least one mastery promotion before receiving the intervention and whose progress on Khan Academy is unsupervised by someone else (like a parent or teacher). Experienced, uncoached users earned 13% more level 3 masteries over the next 30 days if assigned to the treatment group. This effect appeared to maintain over time.

Future Directions

In light of these findings, we intend to replicate this experiment focusing only on the uncoached users who appear to benefit from these messages. We will also continue to monitor the longer term effects on participants in this initial experiment.

Detailed Methods

Dependencies

This analysis requires several libraries and helper functions.

library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(texreg)
library(reshape2)

# Load HELPER FUNCTIONS
source("~/perts_analyses/challenge belanger analyses/helper_functions.R")

Variable Definitions

See Belanger Data Prep for the code used to calculate variables.

Baseline Variables

  • skill_change_pre the number of skill points earned in the 30 days prior to the intervention start
  • condition control or treatment
  • coached whether the user has a coach assigned (i.e, whether they are supervised on Khan Academy by a teacher, parent, or someone else)
  • newbie whether the person earned any masteries in the 30 days prior to treatment

Outcome Variables

  • skill_change the number of skill points earned
  • improved_log log of the number of skill points earned
  • improved_bin whether or not the user exhibited a growth in skills
  • mastery3 number of level 3 masteries earned
  • mastery3_log log of number of level 3 masteries earned
  • mastery3_bin whether or not the user earned at least 1 level 3 mastery
  • mastery1 like mastery3 but for level 1
  • mastery1_log like mastery3_log but for level 1
  • mastery1_bin like mastery3_bin but for level 1
  • total_active_hours number of unique hours user was on site

Datasets

There are two datasets, each of which contain data from the day students were exposed to the intervention (day 0), the 30 days prior to exposure, and the 30 days following exposure.

w has all pre and post outcomes aggregated to the user level. Pre-exposure days are marked pre.

d has outcomes aggregated to the level of each day for each user.

# Load Pre-Processed Data
setwd("~/Dropbox/studies/ka belanger")
d <- read.csv("daily.csv",stringsAsFactors=FALSE)
w <- read.csv("wide.csv",stringsAsFactors=FALSE)

Condition Effects on Mastery

How Are Users Skills Changing as a Result of Intervention?

Visualize changes in masteries by each subgroup and condition.

gdf <- group_by(w, newbie, coached, condition ) %.%
  summarise( mastery3=mean(mastery3) ,
             mastery3_bin=mean(mastery3_bin),
             mastery1=mean(mastery1) ,
             mastery1_bin=mean(mastery1_bin),
             total_active_hours=mean(total_active_hours)
             )

# melt the data for graphing
m <- melt( gdf , id.vars=c("condition","coached","newbie") )

# graph of absolute effects on various outcomes
ggplot( m, aes( condition, value, fill=condition ) ) +
  geom_bar( stat="identity", position="dodge" ) +
  facet_grid( variable ~ newbie + coached, scales="free"  ) +
  xlab("") + ylab("Progress") +
  fill_conditions_scale + ht

Effects on Binary Outcomes

Because of the unusual distributions, we repeat the analyses above using binary outcomes. Using as an outcome whether students mastered any concepts (rather than the number of concepts they mastered), uncoached veterans in the treatment group were ~6% more likely to earn a level 3 mastery over the next 30 days. In contrast, coached users in the treatment condition became ~1% less likely to master a new skill.

# the three-way interaction
model <- glm( mastery3_bin ~ condition * coached * newbie +
            skill_change_pre, 
            data=w,
            family="binomial"
            )

Masteries Over Time

The positive effect on learning among uncoached veterans appears unabated over time, at least in relative terms to the control condition. In contrast, the negative effects among coached users seem to reverse over time. The first set of graphs below shows the absolute levels of progress. The second set of graphs shows treatment progress scaled relative to the matched control group.

Absolute Mastery Progress

gdf <- group_by(d[d$post==1,], condition, newbie, coached, day ) %.%
  summarise( mastery3=mean(mastery3) ,
             mastery3_bin=mean(mastery3_bin)
             )

# melt the data for graphing
library(reshape2)
m <- melt( gdf , id.vars=c("condition","coached","day","newbie") )

# absolute effects on various outcomes
ggplot( m, aes( day, value, linetype=newbie, color=condition ) ) +
  geom_path() +
  facet_grid( variable ~ coached, scales="free"  )  +
  color_conditions_scale + ht

Relative Mastery Progress

Mastery treatment progress scaled relative to the matched control group, i.e., control group progress = 100 for each given day.

# scale the effect by the control group, i.e., control group = 100
gdf <-merge( m[m$condition %in% "Treatment",] ,
             m[m$condition %in% "Control",] ,
             by=c("coached","newbie","day","variable"),
             suffixes=c("_treatment","_control")
             )
gdf$es <- gdf$value_treatment / gdf$value_control * 100
gdf$es[ is.na(gdf$es) ] <- 100

ggplot( gdf[order(gdf$day),], aes( day, es, linetype=newbie ) ) +
  geom_path() +
  geom_smooth( se=FALSE, method="lm", size=2 ) +
  geom_hline( yintercept=100 ) +
  ylab("Progress Compared to Matched Control, Where Control=100") +
  facet_grid( variable ~ coached, scales="free"  ) +
  ht

Supplemental Analysis of Engagement

To investigate the cause of the difference in effect between coached and uncoached users, we examined active hours spent on site. We thought that maybe coached users tend to spend a fixed amount of time on site (because theyre in class) whereas uncoached users spend a flexible amount of time on site. If that were the case, it would be plausible that treatment had a negative effect on coached users by distracting them but a positive effect for uncoached users by motivating them to spend more time work.

In fact, there were no significant effects of condition on time-on-site.

ggplot( w, 
  aes( condition, total_active_hours, fill=condition ) ) +
  geom_bar( stat="summary", fun.y="mean" ) +
  fill_conditions_scale +
  ylab("Unique Hours on Site") +
  facet_grid( . ~ coached + newbie , scales="free"  ) +
  ht

aggregate( total_active_hours ~ condition + 
           newbie + coached,
           data=w , mean ) %>%
  pretty_table()
condition newbie coached total_active_hours

2 Treatment Newbie Coached 5.96
3 Control Veteran Coached 11.21
4 Treatment Veteran Coached 11.44
5 Control Newbie Uncoached 1.55
6 Treatment Newbie Uncoached 1.51
7 Control Veteran Uncoached 9.85
